sec.p:
For KA channels, the differential kinetics and voltage-dependencies of the channel for proximal (radial distance, x ≤ 100 µm from the soma) and distal (x > 100 µm from the soma) regions were accounted for (Hoffman et al., 1997; Migliore et al., 1999). The density of KA channel was set to increase linearly (Hoffman et al., 1997) as a function of distance of the dendritic compartment from soma (Supplementary Table S1):
(2)
gKA(x)=gKAsoma(1+gKAfold100x) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} g_{K A}(x)=g_{K A}^{\text {soma }}\left(1+\frac{g_{K A}^{\text {fold }}}{100} x\right) \tag{2} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
The distribution and kinetics of HCN channels were adapted from previous studies of the hippocampal recordings for pyramidal neurons (Magee, 1998; Narayanan and Johnston, 2007). The kinetics and densities of HCN channels in basal dendrites were set the same as that of soma. The gradient of maximal conductance of HCN followed a sigmoidal dependence along the radial distance, x, of the somatoapical arbor (Supplementary Table S1):
(3)
gh(x)=g¯h(1+ghfold1+exp⁡(ghhmp−xghslope)) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} g_{h}(x)=\bar{g}_{h}\left(1+\frac{g_{h}^{\text {fold }}}{1+\exp \left(\frac{g_{h}^{\text {hmp }}-x}{g_{h}^{\text {slope }}}\right)}\right) \tag{3} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
For apical dendrites, the conductance of the T-type calcium (CaT) channels was set to increase with radial distance as a sigmoid function (Supplementary Table S1):
(4)
gCaT(x)=g¯CaT(1+gCaTfold1+exp⁡(gCaThmp−xgCaTslope)) \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} g_{C a T}(x)=\bar{g}_{C a T}\left(1+\frac{g_{C a T}^{\text {fold }}}{1+\exp \left(\frac{g_{C a T}^{\text {hmp }}-x}{g_{C a T}^{\text {slope }}}\right)}\right) \tag{4} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
The CaT conductance for basal dendritic compartment were set to be the same as that of the soma.

Cross-correlation was computed between the time series of soma-adjacent LFP and the associated somatic voltage. The lag (τ) corresponding to the maximum correlation was computed, and T (= 1⁄f) represented the time-period of the respective oscillation. The phase difference between the intracellular and extracellular waveforms (ϕDE, in degrees) was calculated as:
(7)
ϕIE=360×τT \begin{document}$$\displaystyle \begin{equation*} \phi_{I E}=360 \times \frac{\tau}{T} \tag{7} \end{equation*}$$\end{document}
